Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from the fundamental challenge in multi-contrast MRI reconstruction: ensuring strict data consistency across different contrasts while preserving contrast-specific anatomical details. Existing methods, such as those using range-null space decomposition (e.g., Paper 2), focus on separating consistent (range) and variable (null) components but often treat these subspaces independently or rely on handcrafted priors that may not fully capture complex tissue geometry. Inspired by graph-based regularization in metric learning (Papers 1 and 3), I propose integrating geometric structural constraints—derived from shared anatomical manifolds—into deep learning frameworks via a novel prior formulation grounded in range-null decomposition. Unlike previous approaches that apply null-space manipulation heuristically within unfolding networks, my idea introduces *geometric consistency* as a learnable, contrast-invariant prior enforced through graph-regularized latent embeddings. This ensures that even when individual contrasts exhibit noise or undersampling artifacts, their reconstructions remain anatomically coherent. The key innovation lies in jointly modeling the shared spatial manifold (via range-space graph consistency) and contrast-specific variations (via structured null-space excitation), enabling both strict data fidelity and minimal information loss. By embedding graph-based metric regularization into the physics-driven decomposition framework, this approach transcends current decoupling strategies and offers a principled way to unify interpretability, consistency, and generalization.

