  "Idea": "We propose a novel paradigm titled 'Self-Correcting Manifold Alignment with Evolving Metric Priors' (SCMA-EMP), a next-generation framework for multi-contrast MRI reconstruction that fundamentally rethinks how range-null space decomposition can enforce strict data consistency without sacrificing contrast-specific information. Unlike prior methods that assume the range space is intrinsically consistent, SCMA-EMP recognizes that decomposition errors—arising from noise, motion, or inaccurate sensitivity maps—can propagate into anatomical inaccuracies. To address this, we introduce a bidirectional, self-correcting architecture where the range and null spaces interact iteratively through a shared dynamic manifold. At the core of our method is a Multi-Scale Metric Distortion Loss (MS-MDL), inspired by deep metric learning principles but extended to medical imaging manifolds. MS-MDL operates on patch-level embeddings extracted across all contrasts and enforces hierarchical consistency by regularizing pairwise Euclidean and angular distances in latent space across three levels: (1) Local (within-structure homogeneity, e.g., white matter patches), (2) Regional (boundary sharpness between tissues), and (3) Global (topological connectivity across brain regions). These distance constraints are not static; they evolve during training via a lightweight meta-network that predicts optimal margin thresholds based on estimated tissue uncertainty, derived from ensemble variance in early reconstructions. This allows the model to adaptively relax constraints in ambiguous regions (e.g., lesion boundaries) while tightening them in well-defined anatomy. Additionally, we replace the conventional fixed-range assumption with a Self-Correcting Range Refinement (SCRR) module: after initial decomposition, the null-path generates a residual-driven correction map that identifies potential inconsistencies in the range component (e.g., ghosting, blurring) and refines it before feeding into the Graph-Regularized Manifold Encoder. This turns the traditionally open-loop decomposition into a closed-loop process, ensuring that both subspaces contribute to final consistency. The dual-path network—now symmetric in influence—uses cross-attention gates to allow selective fusion of high-frequency details from the null path without violating manifold structure. During inference, the final image satisfies Ax = y exactly by design, since reconstruction occurs in the full space post-recombination. By integrating evolving metric priors with bidirectional subspace correction, SCMA-EMP achieves unprecedented levels of anatomical plausibility and quantitative accuracy, particularly under extreme undersampling (R > 8). This work bridges interpretability, geometric learning, and adaptive regularization, setting a new benchmark for trustworthy, clinically viable multi-contrast MRI reconstruction.",
